prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: B7 dust+line; Fields 16-143
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: We propose to measure the dust continuum and spectral line emission for 404 young stars in the Orion Nebula cluster in order to determine disk masses, survival timescales, surface density profiles and molecular gas content.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We will also target the CO(3-2), HCN(4-3), HCO+(4-3), and CS(7-6) lines. The expected line widths are ~3-10km/s, so we will use a channel spacing of 0.244 MHz, which will be Hanning smoothed and spectrally averaged (N=2) to a spectral resolution of 0.5 km/s. The resolution used is the same as in Cycle 0 observations of the Orion disks, which clearly revealed velocity gradients in several disks (see Figure 3; Williams et al. 2014; Bally et al., submitted; Hughes et al. in prep).

We request 0.5 arcsec resolution in order to distinguish individual disks, which are clustered together, some less than an arcsecond apart, near the O-star, Theta 1 Ori C (see Figure 2), and to resolve the dust-disk emission for the largest Orion disks. The largest angular scale is based on the extent of the largest disk in Orion, 216-0939, which is 2.6 arcsec in size.

We request observations with ALMA using its Band 7 (870 micron) receivers to measure the dust and gas in protoplanetary disks around 404 young stars in the Orion Nebula Cluster. We will survey 123 pointings to a depth of 1-sigma ~ 0.25 mJy/beam (3-sigma ~ 0.3 Mjup), which can be achieved in 1.2 minutes per pointing (2.5 hours on-source) as calculated by the ALMA OT, using 2nd octile weather conditions, and an aggregate bandwidth of 4.7 GHz.
Our proposed RMS of 0.25 mJy corresponds to a 3-sigma mass sensitivity of 0.3 Mjup, which, as mentioned in the scientific justification, will allow us to detect masses comparable to the deep JCMT-SCUBA survey in nearby Taurus and reveal the full disk mass distribution in Orion. The ability to detect sub-Jupiter mass disks is essential in Orion, as theoretical models predict these disks are rapidly photoevaporated to small sizes (< a few AU) and low masses (< few Jup), if they are located near Theta1-Ori C due to the extreme-UV radiation (Johnstone et al. 1998; Adams et al. 2004). Already completed ALMA Cycle 0 and Cycle 1 observations of Orion disks have, in fact, revealed numerous disks having such low (sub-Jupiter) masses (see Figure 1; Mann et al. 2014).
Diameters of the target disks range between <0.15"-2.6", or <60 AU-1040 AU at 400 pc, the distance to Orion. If a typical 20 K Taurus disk was placed at the distance of Orion in a 0.5" beam, and an appropriate beam filling factor was applied, the observed line temperatures would range between 3 K and 20 K. The ALMA sensitivity calculator estimates an rms noise temperature of 1.3 K for these observations, which is sufficient to detect even cold molecular gas in these disks.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Protoplanetary disks, or "proplyds," are the sites where new Solar systems are born. While most disk studies to date have focused on regions like Taurus for their proximity, stars rarely form in such isolated environments. In fact, there is clear evidence that our own Sun formed near a clustered OB association like Orion. To understand how planets form, it is imperative that we study disk properties in regions representative of their origins. For this reason, we propose to survey the protoplanetary disks around 404 young stars in Orion to study fundamental disk properties in a high-mass star-forming region. We will measure the masses and survival timescales of these disks, study their molecular gas emission and spatially resolve the dust emission of the largest disks in Orion. The results of such observations will provide a detailed view into how the clustered environment and UV radiation affect disk properties and evolution, and ultimately, allow us to assess the potential to form Solar system analogs in a high-mass star-forming region.
